   \"target_achievement\": 0.87,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Directly implements the Ritson & Sutherland (2012) UV cyanometallate photoredox system generating glycolonitrile/glycolaldehyde, then standard Strecker. Strong literature support. rxn_004 stoichiometry is oversimplified (HCN + H\u2082O \u2192 glycolonitrile omits the iterative, multi-HCN photoredox mechanism and copper cycling), but the overall concept is correct. Lacks hydrothermal origin step, so environmental progression is Surface\u2192Biochemical only.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify stoichiometry of rxn_004: the actual mechanism involves multiple HCN molecules and iterative Cu-cyanide photoredox cycling\", \"Consider adding a hydrothermal HCN generation step for fuller environmental span\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_004\": 0.82, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_008\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"Excellent pathway combining Ritson & Sutherland (2012) UV chemistry with their (2018) bisulfite protection strategy. This directly addresses the glycolaldehyde stability bottleneck highlighted in the literature. The bisulfite-protection\u2192Strecker sequence is one of the most experimentally grounded routes to serine aminonitrile. Minor concern: like P2, lacks hydrothermal feedstock generation.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same stoichiometry clarification for rxn_004 as P2\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_004\": 0.82, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_012\": 0.83},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.83,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Implements Green et al. (2023) formamide route. Supported by literature but formamide (mol_013) has no production reaction in the network\u2014it appears as an intermediate without any source, which is a significant gap. The FoSer-CN formation and hydrolysis are experimentally documented. The branching/competing product issue (FoDHA-CN etc.) noted in Green et al. should be acknowledged.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add a reaction producing formamide (e.g., HCN partial hydration or concentration from dilute aqueous HCN)\", \"Acknowledge competing product formation (dehydroalanine nitrile derivatives) from Green et al. (2023)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_003\": 0.75, \"rxn_008\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.87,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Full Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical chain with bisulfite protection. Strongest environmental flow of all pathways. Combines hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation with the most experimentally grounded surface protection chemistry. The formate\u2192formaldehyde step remains a bottleneck. Excellent alignment with Ritson & Sutherland (2018) and the literature emphasis on bisulfite protection solving the glycolaldehyde stability problem.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen evidence for rxn_002 or consider alternative formaldehyde sources\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_003\": 0.75, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_012\": 0.83},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"Combines hydrothermal formaldehyde with formamide chemistry. Reasonable but accumulates two weaker steps (rxn_002 and missing formamide source). Environmental flow is good.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add formamide source reaction\", \"Strengthen rxn_002 evidence\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_006\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_007\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"Interesting pathway that routes through cyanohydrin formation (rxn_006) then UV photoreduction before Strecker. The cyanohydrin step is very well-established chemistry. The UV photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde adds an interesting loop. Good environmental flow from hydrothermal to surface UV to biochemical.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether the glycolonitrile\u2192glycolaldehyde UV reduction step (rxn_005) is well enough characterized for this pathway length\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_006\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_008\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Longest pathway (7 steps) but each step is individually well-supported. The extra length introduces yield attrition concerns. Combines the strongest protection strategy (bisulfite) with hydrothermal feedstock generation and cyanohydrin routing. Coherent but possibly over-elaborate.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether 7 sequential steps is prebiotically plausible given cumulative yield losses\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_006\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_012\": 0.83},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Routes through hydrothermal formaldehyde, cyanohydrin, UV reduction, then formamide chemistry. Combines multiple weak points (rxn_002 and missing formamide source). Still coherent but at the lower end of acceptable.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add formamide production step\", \"This is the longest weak pathway; consider pruning\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_006\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.78, \"rxn_008\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.87,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Surface-only pathway starting from cyanohydrin formation. Well-supported chemistry throughout. Lacks hydrothermal origin steps so environmental progression is limited. The cyanohydrin\u2192UV\u2192bisulfite\u2192Strecker sequence is chemically clean.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Consider adding hydrothermal feedstock generation to enhance environmental span\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an excellent synthesis network for prebiotic serine that is strongly grounded in the experimental literature. The five hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glycolonitrile, serine aminonitrile) are well-chosen and properly connected, creating meaningful convergence. The network faithfully implements three major experimentally demonstrated routes: (1) Ritson & Sutherland (2012) UV cyanometallate photoredox chemistry, (2) Ritson & Sutherland (2018) bisulfite-protected Strecker synthesis, and (3) Green et al. (2023) formamide N-formylaminonitrile chemistry. The Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental flow is correctly maintained with no back-flow. Key strengths: (a) multiple convergent pathways to glycolaldehyde and serine aminonitrile, (b) explicit literature citations in strategy, (c) addresses the glycolaldehyde stability bottleneck via bisulfite protection, and (d) two distinct final hydrolysis routes to serine. Notable issues: (1) Formamide (mol_013) appears as an intermediate but has no